2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) ‘bird, young bird’, also ‘young man, young woman, child’.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’, in particular <i>Ó hÉinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Ó hÉanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Ó hÉanacháin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an Déaghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that which is due or proper’, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉignigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éigneach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘forceful’. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Ó hÉinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or ‘translated’ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>éan</i> ‘bird’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bird was born about 1487, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Bird, was 28 and his mother, Mrs Bird, was 29. He had at least 1 daughter with Betty. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"abt 1487–":"umbes 1487–Surnud","1487–Male":"1487–Surnud","1492–Female":"1492–Surnud","1510–1545":"1510–1545","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1487":"1487","about 1486":"umbes 1486","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","abt 1487":"umbes 1487","Oxford, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1487–":"noin 1487–Kuollut","1487–Male":"1487–Kuollut","1492–Female":"1492–Kuollut","1510–1545":"1510–1545","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1487":"1487","about 1486":"noin 1486","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","abt 1487":"noin 1487","Oxford, England":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England",", , , England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1487–":"environ 1487–Décédé","1487–Male":"1487–Décédé","1492–Female":"1492–Décédée","1510–1545":"1510–1545","1460–Male":"1460–Décédé","1460–Female":"1460–Décédée","1545":"1545","1510":"1510","1487":"1487","about 1486":"environ 1486","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","abt 1487":"environ 1487","Oxford, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre",", , , England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Thomas Bird est né environ 1487, à Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Adam Bird, avait 28 ans et sa mère, Mrs Bird, avait 29 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Betty. Il est décédé à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"abt 1487–":"um 1487–Verstorben","1487–Male":"1487–Verstorben","1492–Female":"1492–Verstorben","1510–1545":"1510–1545","1460–Male":"1460–Verstorben","1460–Female":"1460–Verstorben","1545":"